cs.CV, cs.CL, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.MM

This paper deals with the task of visually grounding linguistic phrases in images, which is a problem at the intersection of computer vision and natural language processing. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). However, the paper also introduces a novel structural loss function that makes use of the parse tree structures induced by the sentences, which is a technique commonly used in natural language processing. Therefore, it is also likely to belong to cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also proposes an end-to-end model that learns visual groundings of phrases, which involves training a neural network, making it likely to belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper uses weakly-supervised learning, which is a common technique in artificial intelligence, making it likely to belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the paper evaluates its approach on two popular datasets in computer vision, making it possible to belong to cs.MM (Multimedia).
